79":"1179","1135":"1135","about 1154":"about 1154","1209":"1209","after 1179":"after 1179","Cataluña, España":"Catalonia, Spain","Sant Iscle de Colltort, Sant Feliu de Pallerols, Girona, Catalonia, Spain":"Sant Iscle de Colltort, Sant Feliu de Pallerols, Girona, Catalonia, Spain","France":"France","Spain":"Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Guillem","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"el","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered short form of   Terry   or   Terence  , of recent origin. For the substitution of <i>-l</i> for <i>-r</i>,  compare  Hal ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Rico\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern short form of both   Nicholas   and   Nicola .  As a boy's name it is also used independently."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillem \"el Rico\" Vizconde de Cardona was born about 1154, in France, his father, Ramón Folc Vizconde de Cardona, was 20 and his mother, Isabel Sibila de Urgel, was 26. He married Géralda de Jorba I d'Alcarràs in Spain. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 3 daughters. He died on 13 July 1225, at the age of 72."},"et":{"about 1154–13 July 1225":"umbes 1154–13. juuli 1225","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1154–1225":"1154–1225","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","–1270":"–1270","1135–1176":"1135–1176","1130–1163":"1130–1163","1190":"1190","17 January 1152":"17. jaanuar 1152","1176":"1176","1154":"1154","3 March 1176":"3. märts 1176","1241":"1241","1163":"1163","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","13 July 1225":"13. juuli 1225","1270":"1270","1159":"1159","1225":"1225","1179":"1179","1135":"1135","about 1154":"umbes 1154","1209":"1209","after 1179":"pärast 1179","Cataluña, España":"Catalunya, Hispaania","Sant Iscle de Colltort, Sant Feliu de Pallerols, Girona, Catalonia, Spain":"Sant Iscle de Colltort, Sant Feliu de Pallerols, Girona, Catalunya, Hispaania","France":"Prantsusmaa","Spain":"Hispaania"},"fi":{"about 1154–13 July 1225":"noin 1154–13. heinäkuuta 1225","1152–1209":"1152–1209","1154–1225":"1154–1225","1159–Female":"1159–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1179–Female":"1179–Kuollut","1190–1241":"1190–1241","1190–Female":"11